content.description:
This is also a very cool boulder problem. When walking down the trail, Thanatopsis is located in a little cove.  

  Start with a sit start and work you way straight up. Both walls are off (aka- no stemming). After pulling through the two small roofs. Either end after the big ledge or if you are on top-rope all the way up. I have never done it on top-rope because the boulder section is the best.
content.protection:
The landing is very slanted on this one. A spotter would ease the fear of falling.  

  Thanatopsis means a view of death. If you have no spotter this definition will make sense.

content.description:
Conformist follows the obvious crack on the right side of the face. 

  A bouldery start leads you to the crack. The crux soon follows as you attempt to mantle onto the major ledge. Some moderate moves take you to the large roof at the top. Traverse the bottom of this to the left.
content.location: Crack on the right side of the face.

content.description:
Steep, hard limestone climbing at its best.  Definitely some of High Cliff's hardest and best climbing. 

  I'm not sure if any specific routes exist here, but a great place to set a toprope and play around.
